Introduction

The COVID 19 pandemic has created large influences on the economy, education, and healthcare worldwide. With the continuous consequences of the COVID, people are curious about the key factors which affect the postive rate per capita. Under such circumstances, we are motivated to find factors that connect closely to the postive rate per capita of the COVID-19. And making an appropriate prediction model which is generated by the linear lasso model. We choose to use the lasso model in this report because the parameters are relatively small here. And it is good at minimizing prediction errors.

5 datasets are sorted, filtered, and merged to form the final dataset for analysis. The main dataset we are using here is the COVID-19 global data from the World Health Organization(WHO), which is a daily record of the COVID-19 cases and death cases corresponding to countries with the WHO region code. The data is significant since WHO is an official agency of the United Nations (UN), which holds the responsibility of guiding global public health. The other four datasets come from the United Nations Development Programme(UNDP), the University of Oxford, and Kaggle(raw data is from Worldometer).

The WHO dataset contains global data from 2020/01/02 to 2021/03/02, but we only use the data on 2021/03/01 to make an easier manipulation. Also, the WHO region code would be used for continental classification. The key dependent variable in this project is the postive rate per capita for COVID 19 by country. Independent variables we are choosing here are data that can strongly indicate the situation of the population, economy, and health system. The basic unit here is per individual country. And the final data is filtered carefully by the COVID stringency index.

The results of the report are meaningful because it shows the relationship between the COVID 19 infection rate and the population, economy, health system, along with a relatively accurate prediction.

Background

Final dataset is created by the manipulation of merging 5 datasets. The categories of the dataset can be classified mainly as postive rate per capita, population, region, economy and health system. And there are 153 countries studies in this project.

For the infection, we are looking at the infected rate, it is originally the cumulative infection cases in the WHO data. We transformed the cumulative cases into the postive rate per capita in this report infected rate = cumulative cases/popluation of the specific country. We are doing the transformation because we want to minimizing the effect of population base when we are considering the effect of independent variables. It is not fair to compare the infected cases together while the denominator is quite different. For example, if one party has 100 people, and another has 1000 people. Both of them has 50 infected cases for COVID 19. It would be very inappropriate saying that the COVID conditions are the same for the two parties.

The population is interpreted such by the total population number, land area, population density, urban population percent. The region is grouped into 6 WHO region: African Region(AFRO), Region of the Americas(AMRO), South-East Asia Region(SEARO), European Region(EURO), Eastern Mediterranean Region(EMRO), and Western Pacific Region(WPRO).

The economy is interpreted by GDP per capita.

The health system is interpreted by the health expenditure, in % of GDP.

In summary, the final dataset contains:

  • postive rate per capita variable: infected_rate

  • demography variable: WHO_region

  • population variable: Population 2020, Pop_yearly_change, Net.Change, population_density, land_area, Migrant_net_change, Fert_rate, median_age,urban_population_percent"

  • economy variable: GDP_per_capita

  • health system variable: health_expenditure_of_GDP

There are 14 variables in this data set:

*infected_rate: it is the Positive rate per capita for each observations during the period of 2020/01/02 to 2021/03/01, calculated by cumulative cases over Population

*WHO_region: it is the WHO region of the observation.

*Population2020: This columns contains the population of different countries in 2020

*Pop_yearly_change :This columns contains the population percentage change by yearly in 2020. For example, 2.33= 2.33%

*Net.Change:This columns contains the net change of the population in 2020

*population_density:The column contains the density of the population (P/Km) in 2020

*land_area:This column contain the land area in terms of kilometer square in 2020

*Migrant_net_change:This column represents the migrants of the countries in 2020

*Fert_rate:This column represents the fertility or the growth rate of individual countries in 2020. (percentage change).For example, 2.33= 2.33%

*median_age:This column represents the median age (Middle Age or the average age) lifespan of the country in 2020

*urban_population_percent:This column represents the urban population

*GDP_per_capita:This represent the GDP per capita for each observation in 2020

*health_expenditure_of_GDP: This represents the health expenditure as a percentage of GDP in 2017(the most recent data). For example: 2.33= 2.33%

*median_stringency: The nine metrics used to calculate the Government Stringency Index are: school closures; workplace closures; cancellation of public events; restrictions on public gatherings; closures of public transport; stay-at-home requirements; public information campaigns; restrictions on internal movements; and international travel controls. For detail calculations of the index, please see this page: https://github.com/OxCGRT/covid-policy-tracker/blob/master/documentation/index_methodology.md

Inferential Analysis

COVID-19 has grabbed our attention since it was reported to the WHO on December 31, 2019. The outbreak of COVID-19 rapidly rises globally pandemic panic, and infected patients are diagnosed as an acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus. The number of deaths and infections are changing day by day, we can obtain the most up-to-date information from both WHO (World Health Organization) and CDC (Centers for Disease Control and Prevention). For this inferential part, we combine a pre-obtained raw dataset from the WHO with some open regional indicators. We are interested in the true meanings behind the large number of infection counts through time and across regions. We consider explaining the rate of infections by those indicators. Ultimately, the results we will derive would have meanings for future predictions on infections and the rate.

To see the objective laws of changing infected rate across regions, we consider using Lasso regression, Ridge regression and Elastic net. The basic idea of them is the same in terms of they are all linear regressions but they have respectively different pros and cons. In our case, we need to be aware of the problem of overfitting and the effectiveness of sample validations. We need to get acquainted with the bias-variance trade-off problem in the linear regression and how we can solve it with regularization.

The basic model is: y = 0 + 1X1 + 2X2 + + nXn +

Introduction of Notation: y: Response variable. It represents the infected rate across regions. 1,,n: coefficients or parameters of the predictor variables 0: Intercept of the model. An uncaptured amount of variations. X1,,Xn: predictor variables. : Residuals or error terms. Here, 1,,n determine the amount of expected change in the y (response variable) when there is a unit increase in the predictor variables. 0 is a constant and does not change when predictor variables change.

One of the most important idea of Ridge regression is the way it solves the model complexity. As we want to explain the response variable precisely, we often introduce many predictor variables. In this case, the increase in number of predictor variables increases the variances but it decreases the bias. For regularization, we need to find a balance between the extent of variances and bias so that we can get reliable results. The trade-off between them is significant since an increase in variance decreases the bias. They have negative relationship.

Lasso regression is similar to Ridge regression. It also introducesto penalize model complexity. However, it does not penalize sum of squared coefficients. It penalize the absolute values. In this way, Lasso regression inherits the idea of Ridge regression and conducts penalty on non-zero coefficients. The major difference between Lasso and Ridge regression is that Lasso results in zeroed coefficients where can never happen in Ridge.

In this part, we are going partition the samples into test set(20%) and training set(80%), and we use the glmnet function in R to construct lasso, ridge and net elastic models. Through standardized cross validation of 10 folds, we select the best lambda that minimize the mean square error based on the cross validation.

Based on the cross validation plot, we can observe the plot is sparse, which implies that the lasso model might have a best prediction outcome out of the 3 models.

After acquring the best lambda and the model, we use the predict the model on the test set. By this prediction, we can interpret the outcome betas in a similar way of interpreting betas for the linear regression model.

In most cases, we need to apply all three regressions to the data and choose one after comparisons. No one can always outperform and has a higher power in description or prediction than others. Lasso deletes the useless or relatively meaningless variables for the model. The advantage of it is variable selection. Ridge regression has a higher power when there are many parameters affecting the response, while Lasso has a higher power when only a few parameters impacting the response. Elastic net is a combination of the two. It is hard to pre-determine which is better. We need to make comparisons in terms of data.

##              least square lambda     R square        R MSE
## linear lasso        0.0006828899 0.6282345893 0.0173332973
## linear ridge        0.0065185153 0.5427923876 0.0179675385
## elastic net         0.0008577496 0.5927980038 0.0176507992

From the table we can observe that the linear Lasso model has the highest R square value 0.628, the lowest R MSE, whcih is 0.0173332973

Here, R-squared means that approximately 62.8% variability of the response around the true values. It measures the percentage variance for the dependent variables.

MSE measures the difference between estimated values and the actual values(prediction errors). In our case, MSE is 0.0173332973 which is relatively low compared to ridge regression and elastic net regression. Thus we reach a conclusion that the linear lasso regression have the best prediction outcome out of all three. The model is successful to some degree since 62.8% of the variability in response variable can be explained by explanatory variable.

Sensitivity Analysis

Since we use the linear lasso regression for prediction,the model should follow the linear regression assumption: 1: random samples are taken from all groups 2: all groups are independent 3: groups have constant variance 4: errors terms are normally distributed and are independent, no correlation with each other. 5: observations are independent and randomly selected.

# Lasso Model Diagnostic
library(plotmo)
## Warning: package 'plotmo' was built under R version 4.0.4
## Warning: package 'TeachingDemos' was built under R version 4.0.4
plotres(lasso_mod, which = 3) # residual vs. fitted

The above Residuals vs.Fitted plot shows a negative linear pattern on its left half while no patterns detected on its right half. Furthermore, there are 3 extreme values present. Therefore, it might be somehow problematic to assume linear relationship between explanatory variables and response variables.

plotres(lasso_mod, which = 4) # QQ plot

Since the right end is above the normal line, we have more extreme values than normal distribution for right end, which means that it has heavier tails. The confidence level that we constructed is actually smaller than the designed confidence level. Although the graph shows some level of heavier tails compare to Normal distribution, it is reasonable to assume the normality assumption holds because points locate relatively close to the normal line.

# Ridge Model Diagnostic 
plotres(ridge_mod, which = 3)

The above Residuals vs.Fitted plot shows a negative linear pattern on its left half while no patterns detected on its right half. Furthermore, there are 3 extreme values present. Therefore, it might be somehow problematic to assume linear relationship between explanatory variables and response variables.

plotres(ridge_mod, which = 4)

Even though the right tail is above the normal line, most of the residuals approximately follow normal line. Thus, it it reasonable to assume that normality assumption holds.

Conclusion

In this report, we are trying to forecast the future outcomes on COVID-19 infection rate (i.e.positive cases per capita) based on current data by building a predictive model. Data we are using include the daily updated cumulative positive cases from WHO, 2020 population from Kaggle, GDP per capita from the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), and health expenditure in % of GDP from World Bank.

The final model we validated is the linear LASSO regression model because it has the largest R-squared value and smallest RMSE value among three models which are LASSO, ridge, elastic net. Due to the penalty algorithm of LASSO, 12 variables are shrunk to 7 since the coefficients of 5 variables are reducing to absolute zero. From the fitted model, we predict that the greater the population density higher the infection rate, smaller the land area higher the infection rate, more migrants of a country higher the infection rate, greater the age higher the infection rate, higher urban population percent higher the infection rate, greater stringency index higher the infection rate.

The predictive outcomes could provide meaningful suggestions on policy regarding COVID-19 regulations so that we could lower the infection rate. For example, further enhancing the practice of social distancing especially in high population density counties and urban areas. To reduce the infection rate of immigrants, governments could provide COVID-19 regulation rules in immigrants native languages so that they could better understand and follow the suggestions. We could also suggest family give more attention to the elderly to protect them from catching the COVID-19.

Please note that the current analysis has a few limitations include:

  • Because of the penalty algorithm of LASSO, some coefficients are shrunk to zero to reduce model over-fitting. However, it might result in under-fitting the model and therefore weaken the predictions. Furthermore, since LASSO is an automatic method, it does not allow analysts to think. In some circumstances, analysts would want to keep the variables in the model regardless of the measure of significance.

  • Because we select the cumulative positive cases reported on one particular date, there are no time variables in our analysis. Therefore, it is hard to generalize the conclusion from this report to the future.

  • One of the variables chosen might be time-sensitive because we only take the median of the stringency index (i.e.the strictness of COVID-19 regulation of government) of each country while the original data of stringency index is reported as daily measurement.

  • The model accuracy could still improve on accuracy because there might be some other predictors or confounding variables that also play a role in predicting the outcomes.

match_country_name=function(set1,name1,name2){
  for (val in c(1:length(name1))){
    set1$Country=as.character(set1$Country)
    set1$Country[set1$Country==name1[val]]=as.character(name2[val])
   
   
  }
  
  return(set1)
}

#Lasso approach

library(caret)
library(glmnet)
set.seed(1)
d_rate_table=as.tibble(d_rate_table2)
#partition data into 50 percent. 
index_80percent= createDataPartition(d_rate_table2$infected_rate,p=0.8,list=FALSE,times=1)

#test and training.
train=d_rate_table2[index_80percent,]
test=d_rate_table2[-index_80percent,]


#train=d_rate_table %>% sample_frac(0.8)
#test=d_rate_table %>% setdiff(train)
x_train=model.matrix(infected_rate~.,train)[,-1]
x_test=model.matrix(infected_rate~.,test)[,-1]
y_train=train %>% select(infected_rate) %>% unlist() %>% as.numeric()
y_test=test %>% select(infected_rate) %>% unlist() %>% as.numeric()


lasso_mod=glmnet(x_train,y_train,alpha=1 )
plot(lasso_mod)
cv.train=cv.glmnet(x_train,y_train,alpha=1,type.measure = "mse", standardize = TRUE, nfolds = 10)
plot(cv.train)
best_lam=cv.train$lambda.min


lasso_pred = predict(lasso_mod, s = best_lam, newx = x_test)


r2 <- cv.train$glmnet.fit$dev.ratio[which(cv.train$glmnet.fit$lambda == cv.train$lambda.1se)] 

Rmse_lasso=sqrt(cv.train$cvm[cv.train$lambda == cv.train$lambda.1se])

lasso_coef = predict(lasso_mod, type = "coefficients", s = best_lam)


lasso_coef

#ridge regression 
set.seed(1)
ridge_mod=glmnet(x_train,y_train,alpha=0)
plot(lasso_mod)
cv.train_lasso=cv.glmnet(x_train,y_train,alpha=0,type.measure = "mse", standardize = TRUE, nfolds = 10)




plot(cv.train_lasso)
best_lam_ridge=cv.train_lasso$lambda.min



ridge_pred = predict(ridge_mod, s = best_lam, newx = x_test)


r2_ridge <- cv.train_lasso$glmnet.fit$dev.ratio[which(cv.train_lasso$glmnet.fit$lambda == cv.train_lasso$lambda.1se)] 

Rmse_ridge=sqrt(cv.train_lasso$cvm[cv.train_lasso$lambda == cv.train_lasso$lambda.1se])


ridge_coef = predict(ridge_mod, type = "coefficients", s = best_lam_ridge)

ridge_coef
